# Sudoku (Borland C++ Project Ported to ncurses)

This project is a modern terminal port of the original Borland C++ Sudoku game.
It keeps the classic gameplay style (tag placeholders, score table, save/continue) while rendering in a UTF-8 ncurses terminal.

## Features

- Classic 9x9 Sudoku with boxed 3x3 sections
- Tag-based input for empty cells (A..Z, a..z, then symbols)
- Colored board rendering:
  - fixed numbers: normal/white
  - placeholders: blue
  - player-entered values: red
- End-game preview + full solution view
- Highscore table with pagination
- Continue/save support
- Random puzzle generation

## Requirements

- C++ compiler with C++17 support (`g++` or `clang++`)
- ncurses development library
- UTF-8 terminal/font that supports box-drawing characters

## Build

### macOS (Homebrew ncurses or system ncurses)

```bash
g++ -std=c++17 WSUDOKU.CPP -lncurses -o wsudoku
```

### Linux (if your distro separates wide-char ncurses)

```bash
g++ -std=c++17 WSUDOKU.CPP -lncursesw -o wsudoku
```

If `-lncursesw` is not available on your system, use `-lncurses`.

## Run

```bash
./wsudoku
```

## Main Menu

- `1` Play Sudoku
- `2` Highscores
- `3` Continue saved game
- `4` Set level (`1` to `5`)
- `5` Instructions
- `6` Write File (generate/store random puzzles)
- `7` Read File (view stored puzzles)
- `8` Search File (filter puzzles by level)
- `9` Edit File
- `0` Exit

## Gameplay Controls

When a puzzle starts, empty cells are shown as placeholders.

- Type a placeholder character (for example `A`, `b`, `!`) to select a cell
- Then type a digit `1` to `9` to fill that cell
- Press `0` to save and continue later
- Press `~` to end the game and view final answer + solution

## Data Files

- `sudoku.dat` -> puzzle records
- `player.dat` -> highscore records
- `continue.dat` -> saved in-progress game

Notes:

- `continue.dat` stores one save state (latest save overwrites previous)
- If `sudoku.dat` has an incompatible legacy layout, the program recreates it automatically

## Troubleshooting

### Grid characters look broken

- Make sure terminal encoding is UTF-8
- Use a font with box-drawing support (for example, JetBrains Mono, Menlo, Cascadia Mono)
- Ensure `TERM` is a capable terminal type (`xterm-256color` is recommended)

### Colors are not visible

- Use a terminal that supports ANSI colors
- Avoid `TERM=dumb`

### Highscore table overlaps or clips

- Resize terminal to a reasonable size (recommended 90x28 or larger)
- Relaunch after resizing if your terminal does not redraw cleanly

## Legacy Note

`SUDOKU.CPP` is the older source. Active terminal version is `WSUDOKU.CPP`.
